The halanta characters in l1 (and elsewhere unless otherwise noted) are reduced, simplified and subscript (though the T is barely subscript, while the M is quite low down). 
--><!-- 
The end of l2 is surprising: sādyaḥdyaḥkra is a strange dittography, and there is plenty of space at the end of the line in spite of kthya hanging down from l1, so "ca" was apparently simply forgotten. 
--><!-- 
The gī of bhāgīratthy in l7 may be a correction from thī. 
--><!-- 
In l11 Mirashi reads māhātvya and omits bha along with ktitva. Bha is clearly there, and on the facsimile the text seems to be mahātmya, not māhātvya. 
--><!-- 
Mirashi reads santāna in l13; the plate has sāntāna. 
--><!-- 
The omission of śrī before pr̥thivīsena's name in l14 is strange, perhaps strange enough that śrī should be supplied as an editorial addition. 
--><!-- 
In l15 Mirashi prints rjji and śrī as unclear, though both seem reasonably clear in the facsimile, except that either of the i mātrās could be short or long, which I do not consider important enough to note. On the other hand, he prints pra as clear, but it is nothing of the kind; possibly it is a correction to pra from sva. 
--><!-- 
Mirashi emends pravr̥tasya in l19 to pradattasya. 
--><!-- 
In l20 Mirashi reads (dhu)va instead of my dhava, but dh is clear and there is no trace of an u mātrā attached to it, unless Mirashi saw the tiny horizontal stroke at the bottom right as u. He also emends vāsaka to vāṭake, which may be a good idea, but given the opaqueness of this bit of text, I'd rather not go into conjectures. Also in l20, prativastu is probably correct, but it could just as easily be prativassa. 
--><!-- 
In l21 Mirashi emends vāṭakaḥ to vāṭaka-, and gattāyā to garttāyāṁ. I accept the +r as practically certain, but I'm not sure about the ending. 
--><!-- 
In l22 Mirashi emends dabhā-pathasya pareṇa to darbha-pathasyāpareṇa. 
--><!-- 
Mirashi supplies brāhmaṇebhyo after °caraṇebhyo in l23.. 
